title: For Sale:  Remington model 14 .30 rem pump rifle
postcontent:
Mfg. in 1917, Remington Model 14 .30 rem 'take down' pump rifle in very good condition. Excellent bore and action, fully operationable, normal wear for 95 year old master crafted firearm. These Rifles are a very important part of American Firearms History. Remington Arms enlisted a brilliant Danish Arms Inventor, John Pedersen, to design a firearm to compete head to head with Winchester's Model 1894 lever action rifles. His invention and design of the Model 14 far surpassed the state-of-the-art of firearms of his day. Some have stated that to build and market such a rifle today would cost 3 to $4,000.00. He was way ahead of his time. The ammo is still readily available today and although there were a limited number produced in the Model 14, there are those proud owners who still insist on this being the rifle of their choice when in search of the great white tale deer and other trophy animals. Find one of these just to handle it for a few minutes and you will become a Model 14 believer !
Check the blue book and you will see its priced to sell quickly. www.gunsinternational.com # 100264676 has a Model 14 listed in .22 cal for $1,100.00., www.gunauction.com just sold a model 14 after 53 bids for $776.00.

title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W 3" 357
postcontent:
I have for sale an unique blued S&W 65-5 .357 3" barrel.  It's a heavy barrel with Walnut boot grips with S&W medallions.  No internal lock.  Made in the early '90s.  Sorry, no box or papers.

Before I get multiple emails again trying to school me that S&W never made a blued 65, allow me to explain.

You are all correct. Smith never made a blued 65; it was the model 13.  I am a big Smith collector and own many S&W's, including multiple 3" models (not boasting, just how it is).  I wanted a 3" model 13, but couldn't find one for the longest time.  After speaking with a master gun restorer, he mentioned that there is a new "hot blueing" process designed for stainless.  To his knowledge, or mine, we have never seen or heard of a blued stainless gun, but I was curious.  Keep in mind, when I called S&W about this, they said that was impossible, and couldn't be done (this is why S&W didn't blue it!).  So, I purchased another 65 and took it to my guy to see if this would work.  The gun you see before you is the result.  It turned out beautiful. Only three things wouldn't blue: the trigger, hammer, and case ejector.  Now this gun is the best of both worlds, a 3" revolver that is blued, but corrosion resistant due to the stainless.  Also, worth noting, this process isn't permanent.  By that I mean the bluing can be removed, and you have a stainless gun back. I installed a new pair of Altamont boot grips on it, and added it to the collection.  I hope everyone is now satisified.

So why am I getting rid of it?  Well, wouldn't you know it, I found a collector's grade 13 on-line and purchased it.  So, I have this beautiful gun, but no longer is needed to fill a void in my collection.  This is why I'm getting rid of it.  Might as well let someone else enjoy it.  

So, with that being said, I'm looking for $650 firm or $700 trade.  If the ad is still up, gun is still available.  Thank you,
